A factory’s total manufacturing costs consists of fixed overhead charges (e.g., rent) of $1600 plus $80 per unit produced. The factory’s total cost (<font face="times_new_romanbold_italic">y</font>) can be represented as a function of the total number of  units (<font face="times_new_romanbold_italic">x</font>) thus:<br>
<div class="tabRoundRectLeft" style="position:relative;width:95%;padding:10px; background-color:#009900"><font color="#ffffff"><font face="times_new_romanbold_italic">y</font> = 80<font face="times_new_romanbold_italic">x</font> + 1600<br>(here <font face="times_new_romanbold_italic">m</font> = $ 80 per unit of product and <font face="times_new_romanbold_italic">c</font> = $1600, overhead charges)</font><br></div>
Observe graph to see relationship between costs of production, with respect to per unit produces.<br>]]></screenText>
